Introduction

Exoplanets (planets outside our solar system) are an object of great interest in astronomy, both to scientists and the general public. Many science fiction works explore the possibility of life on these planets, and some consider that we may one day be able to colonize new habitable worlds. On the science side, exoplanets provide insight into how our own solar system was formed, as well as clues about the abundance (or lack thereof) of certain elements within the universe.

Various search efforts have been undertaken to detect exoplanets. The Kepler space telescope was one of the most successful efforts that managed to identify over 2500 exoplanets. The Wide Angle Search for Planets (WASP) is an international initiative that uses telescopes accross the globe to observe stars for signs of exoplanets. Other projects include TESS, UKIRT, HATNet, and CoRoT, just to name a few.

For this project, I have chosen to use data from the NASA Exoplanet Archive, which aggregates data from many exoplanet searching projects into a comprehensive list of exoplanets, their properties, and information about the systems in which they reside. This cumulative data includes an entry for each time a publication is made on an exoplanet. This means that if a planet is measured multiple times or through different methods, the data for each is available. I found this data useful for its comprehensive nature, and in this project, I will use it to examine the strengths and weaknesses of different detection methods, as well as the relationship between exoplanets and their host stars.

First, I need to load the data and relevant libraries and examine the columns of the dataset. Because this dataset has 286 columns, I will exclude column descriptions for error bounds on values as well as columns labeled as flags (boolean values describing the presence or absence of data).

Exploratory Analysis

First, we can look at an overview of how many exoplanets have been discovered per year. I will use the no duplicates dataset for this because I only want to count each exoplanet once.

In [203]:
plt.hist(df_no_dupe["disc_year"], bins=sorted(df_no_dupe["disc_year"].unique()))
plt.title("Exoplanets Discovered vs Year")
plt.show()

There seems to be a steady trend of increased discoveries, with the exception of a few outlier years. The outlier years between 2014 and 2020 are due to the Kepler space telescope being active during that period. NASA announced large batches of discovered planets all at once during that period, which is the reason why some of these years are so much higher than the others.

Next, we can look at planet denisty versus planet radius. From a purely physics perspective, one would expect density to increase as radius increases; the planet experiences a compressive force as mass increases, so in order to maintain a larger radius, the planet must have a higher density to counteract that force. I will graph planet denisty versus radius, using both the with duplicates and no duplicates dataset. I use a log scale on both axes to make the results more clear.

In [211]:
plt.figure()
plt.title("Exoplanet Density vs Exoplanet Radius")
plt.scatter(df_nasa["pl_rade"], df_nasa["pl_dens"], c='tab:blue', label="With Duplicates")
plt.scatter(df_no_dupe["pl_rade"], df_no_dupe["pl_dens"], c='orange', label="No Duplicates")
plt.yscale('log')
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xlabel("Planet Radius (Earths)")
plt.ylabel("Planet Density (g/cm^3)")
plt.legend(loc='lower left')
plt.show()

This plot seems to defy our expectations! As the radius of the planet increases, the density decreases. In addition, two primary clusters can be observed in the points. This can be attributed to the difference between rocky planets and gas giants. Planets with a large radius tend to be gas giants, and their density is low. Conversely, small gas giants don't form (due to the gravity being too weak to hold the gas together), so smaller planets tend to be rocky, and thus have a higher density. The two clusters observed are rocky planets and gas giants.

Although it won't be completely accurate, we can try to apply K-means clustering to the data to apply rocky and gas giant labels to the planets. This could potentially be useful in future analysis. I will label the flag of whether or not the planet is a gas giant as 'pl_type'.

In [345]:
# create training set (KMeans cannot handle NaN)
train = df_nasa.dropna(subset=["pl_rade", "pl_dens"])

# classify the planets
pl_type = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=1).fit(np.c_[train["pl_rade"], train["pl_dens"]])
df_nasa["pl_type"] = list(map(lambda x : np.nan if any(pd.isna(x)) else pl_type.predict([x]),
                              np.c_[df_nasa["pl_rade"], df_nasa["pl_dens"]]))

Next, we can look at the relationship between the planet's equilibrium temperature and its maximum distance from its star. Here, the "semi-major axis" is a metric of the maximum distance the planet reaches from its star during its orbit. However, this graph uses the ratio of the semi-major axis to the radius of the star. The reason for this is because the semi-major axis measures distance to the center of the star, rather than the surface, and although star radius does not directly correspond to the heat flux produced, using the ratio metric produces a clearer relationship. I will put both axes on log scale to better show the relationship.

This graph is fairly straightforward. As the planet gets closer to the star, it gets hotter. This is a very reasonable and intuitive observation.

Examining Methods of Discovery

After observing and recording data from systems, various techniques can be used to discover the exoplanets within them. In this section, I will analyze the use cases and effectiveness of some of these techniques, and hopefully draw some conclusions about the usefulness of each.

First, we can look at the names of the methods in question, as well as how often they are used.

In [201]:
df_nasa["discoverymethod"].value_counts()
Out[201]:
Transit                          30802
Radial Velocity                   2270
Microlensing                       430
Transit Timing Variations          120
Imaging                            113
Eclipse Timing Variations           24
Orbital Brightness Modulation       20
Pulsar Timing                       12
Astrometry                           2
Pulsation Timing Variations          2
Disk Kinematics                      1
Name: discoverymethod, dtype: int64

It seems that the top five methods are much more popular than the rest. To ensure robustness of the analysis, I will only consider the top five methods to ensure that there will be enough data. Brief descriptions of the top five methods are as follows:

  • The transit method involves observing the brightness of a star. When a planet passes in front of the star, the star's brightness will drop. By observing the frequency and size of these brightness dips, orbital period and planet size, among other things, can be determined.
  • The radial velocity method (aka the Doppler method) involves monitoring the wavelength of the light emitted from a star. As a planet orbits around a star, the star can also be said to orbit around the planet. The slight adjustments in the star's position causes the wavelength of the light to undergo a Doppler shift as it oscillates between being closer and father from the Earth. In this way, exoplanets can be detected.
  • Gravitational microlensing involves monitoring light as it lenses around a star. Massive objects can serve as a 'gravitational lense', magnifying the light of objects behind it by warping the space around it. Small fluctuations in the magnifying effect of the gravitational lense can be used to detect the influence of exoplanets.
  • Transit Timing Variations (TTV) is a bit different from the other methods in that it involves the measurement of a known exoplanet. By measuring the variation in period of a known exoplanet, it is possible to deduce the existance of others based on how it is affected.
  • Direct imaging is exactly what it sounds like. But because stars are much brighter than planets, a planet must be significantly seperated from its host star and also very large in order to be detected in this way.

To make analysis easier, I will create a new dataframe that drops all entries besides for the described methods. I will also relabel Transit Timing Variations as TTV for readability purposes.

I will begin by making some graphs to identify what types of objects the methods tend to detect. In the above descriptions of the methods, I mention the variables that each method uses to identify exoplanets. Because they are directly important to the detection methods, I will focus on them for the analysis. In summary, the variables are: orbital period, radius, mass, and number of planets. In addition, orbital inclination is another important variable because many of these methods depend on the exoplanet being in the plane of the Earth and host star.

First, I will look at orbital period and orbital period error.

Imaging and microlensing seem to exclusively capture exoplanets with a very large period. For imaging, this is in line with expectations because a large period also means a far out orbit, which is one of the requirements for detection by this method. For microlensing, the reasoning is not so apparent. It could possibly be due to gravitational lensing being a weak effect, and for a planet to affect it in a noticable way, it needs to take a large orbit to move the center of mass of its system. Radial velocity seems to be able to detect planets of all periods. TTV and transit seem to detect primarily those with lower periods. This is likely due to both methods requiring the brightness of a star to be recorded over a long period of time. Planets that pass in front of the star frequently (aka those with shorter periods) may be more likely to be detected through these methods.

For the error plot, TTV and transit seem to have the best error. Based on both distributions, the error for these two methods seems to be about 0.001%. The other methods do not see such remarkable precision, with the error ranging between 10% and 0.1%.

Next, let's look at planet radius and its error.

We can also look at the number of planets in the system detected. For this graph, it is important not to double count, since, for example, if a system were to have 8 planets, it would be counted 8 times (once for each planet entry). I take a different approach from the other graphs and remove not just duplicate planets, but duplicate systems.

In [607]:
# remove duplicate systems
df_pnum = df_methods.drop_duplicates(subset="hostname", keep="last")

# helper method for counting the number of planets
# we care more about the ratio of the types of planets, so normalize this quantity
def count_p(col):
    count = []
    total = df_pnum.loc[df_pnum["discoverymethod"] == col]["sy_pnum"].count()
    
    for i in range(1, 10):
        count.append(df_pnum.loc[(df_pnum["discoverymethod"] == col) & (df_pnum["sy_pnum"] == i)]["sy_pnum"].count() / total)
    
    return count

# helper method for counting the number of planets for all methods
def count_all():
    count = []
    total = df_pnum["sy_pnum"].count()
    
    for i in range(1, 10):
        count.append(df_pnum.loc[df_pnum["sy_pnum"] == i]["sy_pnum"].count() / total)
    
    return count

# helper method for getting the x location of each bar
def xloc(i):
    return [i * 0.1 + j for j in range(1, 10)]

# graph number of planets
plt.figure()
plt.bar(xloc(0), count_p("Transit"), width=0.1, label="Transit")
plt.bar(xloc(1), count_p("Radial Velocity"), width=0.1, label="Radial Velocity")
plt.bar(xloc(2), count_p("Microlensing"), width=0.1, label="Microlensing")
plt.bar(xloc(3), count_p("TTV"), width=0.1, label="TTV")
plt.bar(xloc(4), count_p("Imaging"), width=0.1, label="Imaging")
plt.bar(xloc(5), count_all(), width=0.1, label="All")

plt.title('Histogram of the Number of Planets in the Systems of Detected Exoplanets')
plt.xlabel('Number of Planets')
plt.yscale('log')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Transit and radial velocity seem to follow the same exponential distribution of all planets, so these methods are likely independent of the number of planets in the system. Microlensing looks more limited in this capacity; it does not detect more than 2 planets in a system. TTV requires at least one planet in the system to be detected through transit, so not detecting single planet systems is expected. However, it seems to be better at detecting systems in the 4 to 5 planet range. Imaging does seem to follow the normal exponential distribution, but interestingly, it does not seem to have detected any systems with 3 planets.

Lastly, we can look at the inclination of planets detected.

In terms of inclination, imaging and radial velocity seem to be the most flexible with what can be detected. TTV and transit on the other hand both seem to require the planets to be almost exactly in-plane for the detection to work. Microlensing also seems to have a somewhat narrow requirement for what it can detect.

Overall, transit is the most effective of the methods. For orbital period, radius, mass, and number of planets, it is able to detect a very large range of values with good precision. The one shortcoming is that this method requires a very specific inclination of a planet in order for it to be detectable. Because transit is the method used for the vast majority of exoplanet discoveries, it is likely that a lot of exoplanets are being missed for not being exactly in-plane. In that regard, more detection via radial velocity would likely turn up good results. In terms of detection range, it is second only to transit, and in terms of inclination it is the most flexible out of all the methods. Therefore, I believe that more comprehensive data on exoplanets could be gathered via the radial velocity method.

On the contrary, out of all the methods, microlensing demonstrates the poorest performance. Not only is it restricted to detecting massive planets with large orbits, but it has very large error bounds on the measurements it makes.

Relating Stars and Planets

In this section, I examine how host stars and their planets are related. This is somewhat of a broad statement, so I will narrow down the scope to one idea. Just from intuition, one interesting relation between host stars and planets is material composition. In other words, if we know what the star is made of, can we predict what possible planets are made of? Stars are much easier to measure than exoplanets, so being able to deduce the properties of exoplanets from their host stars would be a useful tool. The specific quantities of focus are planet density and gas giant vs rocky classification.

Before training any models, let's try to tease out information visually with graphs and linear regression. Note: one planet can have multiple entries, but because quantities vary between entries and there is no way to identify which is the "correct" measurement (if any), I will treat each entry as its own exoplanet.

First, we will look at something straightfoward: star density and planet density. Because planets will form from the materials that gather around stars, it is not unlikely that similar materials go into each.

A couple interesting things can be noted about this graph. First, there does seem to be a clear relationship between planet density and star denisty. Second, not only do gas giants and rocky planets seem to follow distributions, less dense stars seem to have only gas giants and more dense stars seem to have only rocky planets! Let's see if fitting a regression line to each population yields more information. Because there are a lot of outliers in this dataset and Sklearn's LinearRegression is sensitive to this, I will weight the points by the inverse of their z-score.

In [451]:
# first, drop NaN values
train = df_nasa.dropna(subset=["st_dens", "pl_dens"]).copy()

# helper function for calculating the weights
def weight(x):
     return list(map(lambda x : 1 / x**2, zscore(x)))

# (need to use zip on all the inputs because fit() expects the array to look like [[1], [2], [3], ...])
def form(x):
    return list(zip(np.log(x)))

# linear regression on the whole population
gen_reg = LinearRegression().fit(form(train["st_dens"]),
                                 np.log(train["pl_dens"]),
                                 sample_weight=weight(train["st_dens"]))

# print the score of the model
print("General Score:", gen_reg.score(form(train["st_dens"]),
                                      np.log(train["pl_dens"]),
                                      sample_weight=weight(train["st_dens"])))
print(gen_reg.coef_, gen_reg.intercept_)

# linear regression on gas giant population
gasg_reg = LinearRegression().fit(form(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "st_dens"]),
                                  np.log(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "pl_dens"]),
                                  sample_weight=weight(np.log(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "st_dens"])))

# print the score of the model
print("Gas Giant Score:", gasg_reg.score(form(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "st_dens"]),
                                         np.log(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "pl_dens"]),
                                         sample_weight=weight(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 1, "st_dens"])))
print(gasg_reg.coef_, gasg_reg.intercept_)

# linear regression on rocky population
rocky_reg = LinearRegression().fit(form(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 0, "st_dens"]),
                                   np.log(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 0, "pl_dens"]),

# print the score of the model

                                      np.log(train.loc[train["pl_type"] == 0, "pl_dens"]),

Lastly, according to the linear regression model, star metallicity, radius, and mass are the three largest factors towards predicting planet density.

Conclusions

In this project, I used K-Means clustering to create a tentative labeling of gas giants and rocky planets. I then analyzed the qualities of different exoplanet detection methods and drew relationships between host stars and their exoplanets.

I found that the two most effective methods of exoplanet detection are transit and radial velocity. However, transit is restricted in detection by orbital inclination. Because transit is being used for the vast majority of detections, there is scientific merit to increasing the use of radial velocity detection in order to create a more diverse dataset that is not so dependent on inclination.

I also found that it is possible to predict with good accuracy whether a star is more likely to have a rocky planet or gas giant planet. I trained both a random forest and LDA model, and found that they reached 80% accuracy in prediction, whereas random guessing would only achieve 65%. I found that star mass, star metallicity, and star luminocity are the most important features when determining what type of planets a star is likely to have.

I found that predicting planet density based on the star is a difficult problem. I found visible relations between multiple features (star density, radius, and temperature) and planet density, but due to non-linearity in the data, the accuracy of the models suffered. I trained both a linear regression and SVM model to predict planet density from star features. I found that the model suffered at predicting the density of rocky planets, but it performed much better for gas giants. I also found that star metallicity, star radius, and star mass are the most influential features towards determining planet density.
